    "overview": "Operative details regarding By which amendment Article 58-2b... under the category of Islamic History.",
    "question": "By which amendment Article 58-(2)(b) removed from constitution? Association Information: Article 58(2)(b) and Its Evolution Article 58(2)(b), a provision in Pakistan's Constitution, allowed the President to dissolve the National Assembly at their discretion. It underwent significant changes through various amendments, reflecting shifts in the Introduced by General Zia-ul-Haq to grant the President unilateral power to dissolve the National Assembly in cases where governance could not function as per the Constitution. Shifted Pakistan toward system. 13th Amendment (1997): a semi-presidential Context: Removed the President's unilateral power to dissolve the National Assembly. Result: The President could no longer invoke Article 58(2)(b) without the Prime Minister's advice, restoring parliamentary sovereignty. 17th Amendment (2003): General Pervez Musharraf restored Article 58(2) to allow the President to dissolve the National Assembly. Justified as a check and balance on the Prime Minister's authority, but it weakened parliamentary autonomy. 18th Amendment (2010): Under Asif Ali Zardari's government, Article 58(2)(b) was permanently removed. Strengthened parliamentary democracy by ensuring the President could no longer dissolve the National Assembly unilaterally. Key Impacts • • • • 8th Amendment (1985): Established presidential dissolution powers. 13th Amendment (1997): Removed the President's unilateral power to dissolve the National Assembly, making dissolution subject to the Prime Minister's advice. 17th Amendment (2003): Restored the President's powers to dissolve the assembly. 18th Amendment (2010): Fully abolished Article 58(2)(b), reinforcing a parliamentary system. The history of Article 58(2)(b) showcases a struggle for balance between presidential authority and parliamentary democracy in Pakistan. The 13th Amendment marked an important step toward curbing presidential powers, while the 18th Amendment ultimately ensured a stable and sovereign parliamentary system by permanently removing this provision.",
