    "question": "First President of Pakistan, Iskandar Mirza, buried in?",
    "verified_answer": "Tehran",
    "context": "Iskander Mirza: A Comprehensive Overview Iskander Mirza (also spelled as Iskandar Mirza, Iskander Ali Mirza, or Sikandar Mirza) (1899-1969) was a Pakistani politician, statesman, and military general who played a significant role in the country's early years. Born on November 13, 1899 in Murshidabad, Bengal, India, Mirza came from an elite and wealthy aristocratic family with significant business interests. Military Career • • Mirza Joined the British Indian Army in 1920 and served in various positions, Including as a Major General during World War II. After the partition in 1947, he joined the Pakistan Army as a Major General and became a key figure in the country's military and political circles. Notably, Mirza served as both a Major General in the Army and Defence Secretary in 1947, highlighting his unique role in Pakistan's early years. Political Career • • Governor-General: Iskandar Mirza held the shortest tenure as a governor general in Pakistan, serving from October 6, 1955, to March 23, 1956. He was appointed as the Governor-General in 1955 and later became the president when Pakistan's first Constitution was promulgated in 1956. He served as Governor-General for approximately 6 months before assuming the presidency. First President of Pakistan: Mirza became the first president of Pakistan and served from March 23, 1956, to October 27, 1958. • Other Political Roles: o Defence Secretary (1947) o Governor of East Bengal (1954) o Interior Minister (1955) o. Governor-General of Pakistan (1955-1956) o First President of Pakistan (1956-1958) Presidency and Ayub Khan's Takeover • • • During his presidency, Mirza oversaw the implementation of Pakistan's first constitution and played a crucial role in shaping the country's early years. His presidency was cut short when Ayub Khan, who was both the Defence Minister and Commander-in- Chief of the Pakistan Army, ousted him on October 27, 1958. This powerful combination of roles allowed Ayub Khan to seize control of the government and establish a military dictatorship in Pakistan. Despite his controversial legacy, Mirza's political decisions had a lasting impact on Pakistan's development. His family's business Interests and influence continue to be felt in the region. Ayub Khan's takeover marked a significant turning point in Pakistani history, leading to a military dictatorship that lasted for over a decade. It Is essential to acknowledge the complexities of Ayub Khan's role in Pakistani politics and the motivations behind his actions to gain a deeper understanding of the context and implications of this event. Exile and Later Life (1958-1969) Ousted by Ayub Khan in 1958, forced to resign and leave Pakistan. Spent his last years in exile in London, England. Lived a quiet life, away from politics and ublic eye. Passed away on November 13, 1969, in London, at the age of 70. Burial (1969) Denied burial in Pakistan by the government. • Buried in Tehran, Iran, at the Imamzadeh Abdullah Shrine.",
    "reddington_story": "The First President of Pakistan Iskandar... remains a delicate affair. I remember a conversation with a defector in a safehouse near Lisbon. He was terrified of Tehran. I told him fear is a wonderful motivator, provided you know which way to run.",
