    "id": "PPSC-19-0283",
    "division": "Laboratory",
    "subject": "Everyday Science",
    "sub_subject": "General Science",
    "dossier_name": "Why is the Ozone important...",
    "overview": "Operative details regarding Why is the Ozone important... under the category of General Science.",
    "question": "Why is the Ozone important for mankind?",
    "verified_answer": "Protection from ultraviolet rays of sun",
    "context": "Some key points about ozone and the ozone layer: Ozone (03): - Ozone is a molecule composed of three oxygen atoms It is a powerful oxidizing agent and has a pungent, pleasant smell Ozone is created naturally in the stratosphere through the interaction of ultraviolet radiation and oxygen molecules It can also be created artificially through electrical discharges or chemical reactions Ozone Layer: The ozone layer is a region in the stratosphere, about 15-30 km above the Earth's surface - It contains a high concentration of ozone (O3), which absorbs most of the sun's ultraviolet (UV) radiation The ozone layer protects living organisms from UV damage, which can cause skin cancer, cataracts, and other health issues - The ozone layer also helps regulate the Earth's climate and weather patterns Ozone Depletion: Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) and other halogenated gases are the main culprits behind ozone depletion These gases were widely used as refrigerants, propellants, and solvents in various products When released into the atmosphere, they can rise to the stratosphere and catalytically destroy ozone molecules The resulting ozone hole over Antarctica was first discovered in 1985 and has since become an annual occurrence Consequences of Ozone Depletion: Increased UV radiation reaching the Earth's surface. leading to health issues and environmental damage Damage to crops and marine ecosystems Disruption of the Earth's climate and weather patterns International Efforts to Protect the Ozone Layer: The Montreal Protocol, signed in 1987, aims to phase out CFCs and other ozone-depleting substances",
    "reddington_story": "It was the summer of '91, and the heat in Tangier was almost unbearable. I was brokering an agreement that turned entirely on the Why is the Ozone important.... The other side brought a briefcase full of cash, but all I wanted was Protection from ultraviolet rays of sun. Information is the only currency that never depreciates.",
