    "verified_answer": "1990",
    "context": "Nelson Mandela (1918–2013) was a South African anti- apartheid activist, politician, and philanthropist whose life and legacy have left an indelible mark on the world. He is celebrated for his tireless fight against racial inequality and his efforts to build a more just and united South Africa. Anti-Apartheid Activism: Mandela joined the African National Congress (ANC) in 1943 and co-founded its Youth League in 1944. He emerged as a leading figure in the fight against apartheid, a brutal system of racial segregation enforced by the South African government. Initially advocating for nonviolent resistance, Mandela later became involved in organizing acts of civil disobedience and other measures to challenge the oppressive regime. His efforts helped galvanize the anti- apartheid movement and brought international attention to South Africa's plight. Imprisonment: Mandela was arrested in 1962 and spent 27 years in prison, enduring harsh conditions and isolation. Despite this, he remained a steadfast advocate for justice and equality, becoming a symbol of resistance against oppression. His imprisonment became a rallying point for anti-apartheid activists worldwide, and his resilience inspired millions. Presidency and Reconciliation: After his release in 1990, Mandela led negotiations to end apartheid, culminating in South Africa's first multiracial elections in 1994, where he was elected as the country's first black president. As president, he prioritized national reconciliation, establishing the Truth and Reconciliation Commission to address human rights abuses during apartheid. Mandela's leadership was characterized by his focus on forgiveness, unity, and nation-building, helping to heal the deep divisions within South African society. Legacy and Achievements: Mandela's legacy extends far beyond his presidency. He is celebrated globally for his contributions to peace, reconciliation, and social justice. Some of his notable achievements include: • Leading South Africa's peaceful transition to democracy. • Establishing the Nelson Mandela Foundation, which focuses on education, rural development, and HIV/AIDS awareness. • Advocating for women's rights and gender equality. • Receiving over 250 honors and awards, including the Nobel Peace Prize (1993) and the Presidential Medal of Freedom from President Barack Obama. Books by Nelson Mandela Mandela's writings provide a deep insight into his life and ideals: • \"Long Walk to Freedom\" (1994): His autobiography, chronicling his journey from rural South Africa to becoming a global icon. • \"Conversations with Myself\" (2010): A collection of personal reflections, letters, and interviews. • \"Dare Not Linger: The Presidential Years\" (2017): Co-written with Mandla Langa, this book focuses on Mandela's presidency. • \"The Struggle Is My Life\" (1990): A collection of Mandela's speeches and writings, reflecting his vision and commitment to justice.",
    "reddington_story": "The verified details of Nelson Mandela of South Africa... have always been closely guarded. A politician in London swore to me that he had buried the 1990 forever. Two weeks later, his career was in ashes. A circus, really. Secrets always find a way to breathe.",
