    "context": "Greenland and Antarctica: The World's Ice Reservoirs Greenland and Antarctica are the two largest ice bodies on Earth, collectively containing about 99% of the planet's ice. These regions are critical to regulating global climate, sea levels, and weather patterns. Greenland Location: North Atlantic, northeast of Canada and northwest of Europe. Size: Approximately 2.175 million km² (843,000 sq mi). Ice Coverage: About 80% of Greenland is covered in ice, with an average thickness of 1.5-2 km (0.9-1.2 mi). Ice Volume: Approximately 2.5 million km³ (1 million cu mi). Impact: Greenland's melting ice contributes significantly to sea level rise, adding 0.7-1.1 mm (0.03-0.04 in) annually. Antarctica Location: Southern Hemisphere, surrounding the South Pole. Size: Approximately 14 million km² (5.4 million sq mi). Ice Coverage: About 98% of Antarctica is covered in Ice, with an average thickness of 2-3 km (1.2-1.9 mi). Ice Volume: Approximately 30 million km³ (7.2 million cu mi). Impact: Antarctica's vast ice sheet plays a key role in regulating global sea levels, with its potential melting capable of raising sea levels by 3-4 meters (10-13 ft). Comparison Size and Volume: Antarctica Is 6-7 times larger than Greenland and contains about 91% of Earth's ice, compared to Greenland's 8%. Melting Susceptibility: Greenland's ice is more prone to melting due to lower elevation and proximity to warmer ocean currents. • Antarctica's ice is more stable but still vulnerable to climate change and warming ocean currents. Importance Both Greenland and Antarctica are critical to:",
