    "id": "PPSC-19-0806",
    "division": "Archive",
    "subject": "Pakistan Studies",
    "sub_subject": "Pakistan History",
    "dossier_name": "Pakistan's National Anthem was approved...",
    "overview": "Operative details regarding Pakistan's National Anthem was approved... under the category of Pakistan History.",
    "question": "Pakistan's National Anthem was approved by the Government in:",
    "verified_answer": "1954",
    "context": "Pakistan's National Anthem: \"Qaumi Tarānah\" Title: \"Qaumi Taranah\" (قومی ترانه) Lyrics: Written by Hafeez Jullundhri in 1952 Music: Composed by Ahmed Ghulamali Chagla in 1949 Adopted: As the national anthem on August 14, 1954 First played: February 1950, before the King of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, during his visit to Karachi, Pakistan Language: Urdu, with Persian influences Meaning: The anthem is a prayer for the country's. prosperity and unity Structure: Consists of three stanzas, with a total of 26 lines Duration: Approximately 1 minute and 20 seconds Instruments: Typically performed with a combination of eastern and western instruments Significance: Represents Pakistan's commitment to Islam, democracy, and national unity History: - February 1949: Government of Pakistan formed a committee to prepare Pakistan's National Anthem. Out of 723 people who competed, Hafeez Jalandhari's lyrics were selected. - 1949: Ahmed Ghulamali Chagla composed the music - 1952: Hafeez Jullundhri wrote the lyrics - February 1950: First played before the King of Iran - August 14, 1954: Officially adopted as the national anthem Note: The lyrics were written by Hafeez Jullundhri In 1952, but the anthem was first played on March 1, 1950. This means that The tune was then played without lyrics on March 1, 1950, during the Shah of Iran's visit to Pakistan. Later, Hafeez Jullundhri wrote the lyrics In 1952, and the complete anthem (tune and lyrics) was officially adopted on August 14, 1954. Selection Process: - Committee formed in 1949 to select the national anthem - 723 people competed to write the National Anthem - Hafeez Jalandhari's lyrics were selected as the national anthem of Pakistan - Tune selection process: - 6 tunes were shortlisted from over 100 submissions - Ahmed Ghulam Ali Chagla's tune was selected as the final tune - The duration of the National Anthem is 1 minute and 20 seconds (80 seconds). First Recording: - Recorded by a group of renowned singers in 1954 - The recording was done in a single take, with all the singers performing together in the studio - The leading singer of the group that recorded the Pakistani national anthem in 1954 was Ahmed Rushdi. He was a well-known playback singer and music composer in Pakistan, and his powerful and soulful voice was considered ideal for rendering the national anthem. Rushdi was joined by a group of other renowned singers, including Najam Ara, Naseema Shaheen, Zawar Hussain, Akhtar Abbas, Ghulam Dastagir, Anwar Zaheer, Akhtar Wasi Ali, Kaukab Jahan, Rasheeda Begum, and Shamim Bano, to create a memorable and iconic recording of the national anthem. - This recording was done under the supervision of the National Anthem Committee, which was responsible for selecting the final version of the anthem - The recording was done in the Pakistan Broadcasting Corporation (PBC) studios in Karachi. Task of recording was given to EMI. - The recording has been preserved and is still used today as the official version of the national anthem - No other official recording of the national anthem has been made since then, making this the only official recording to date. Summary: Pakistan's national anthem, \"Qaumi Tarānah\", was written by Hafeez Jullundhri in 1952 and composed by Ahmed Ghulamali Chagla in 1949. It was adopted as the national anthem on August 14, 1954, and first played before the King of Iran in February 1950. The anthem has a unique blend of Persian and Urdu languages and is considered one of the most melodious and harmonious anthems in the world. The recording of the anthem was done by a group of renowned singers in 1954 and is still used today as the official version.",
    "reddington_story": "We are all looking for answers, but sometimes 1954 is the last thing you want to find. I watched a young operative in Bogota try to trace the Pakistan's National Anthem was approved.... He was clever, but he didn't realize the web he was stepping into.",
