    "question": "The portion of the wall of Kaba, which is between its door and Hajr-e-Aswad is called",
    "verified_answer": "Al Multazim",
    "context": "The Kaaba, a cube-shaped building in Mecca, Saudi Arabia, is the holiest site in Islam. Its significance is profound, serving as the focal point for Muslims worldwide during their prayers. The Kaaba's walls and corners hold rich history and symbolism, adding depth to its spiritual importance. Walls of the Kaaba: - Hatim (Hijr Ismail): The semi-circular wall adjacent to the Kaaba, believed to be the original construction site by Prophet Ibrahim (Abraham) and his son Ismail (Ishmael). - Wall of the Black Stone (Rukn al-Aswad): The eastern wall featuring the Black Stone (Hajar al-Aswad). - Yemeni Wall (Rukn al-Yamani): The southern wall facing Yemen. - Syrian Wall (Rukn al-Shami): The northern wall, facing Syria and Türkiye. - Iraqi Wall (Rukn al-'Iraqi): The eastern wall, facing Iraq. Corners of the Kaaba: - Rukn al-Aswad (Black Stone Corner): The eastern corner featuring the Black Stone (Hajar al-Aswad), a heavenly stone brought by angel Gabriel to Prophet Ibrahim. Pilgrims touch or kiss it during Hajj as an act of devotion. - Rukn al-Yamani (Yemeni Corner): Located on the southern side, facing Yemen, pilgrims touch this corner during circumambulation (tawaf). - Rukn al-Shami (Syrian Corner): Positioned on the northern side, facing Syria and Türkiye, this corner symbolizes the unity of the Muslim ummah (community) across geographical boundaries. Pilgrims touch it during tawaf. - Rukn al-'Iraqi (Iraqi Corner): The eastern corner, facing Iraq, completes the set. Pilgrims touch or point towards it during their tawaf.",
    "reddington_story": "There is a quiet beauty in Al Multazim, wouldn't you agree? I once saw a collection of files related to The portion of the wall... in a vault in Zurich. The owners thought they were secure behind three feet of steel. They forgot that steel eventually rusts.",
    "visual_mnemonic": "Visualize a classic leather scroll unfurling, with the gold-ink calligraphy of 'Al Multazim' radiating warm light onto a map of Madinah.",
