    "verified_answer": "Nur-ul-Amin",
    "context": "The first and only Vice President in the history of Pakistan was indeed Nurul Amin. He held this position from December 20, 1971, to August 14, 1973, when the post was abolished. Amin also played a significant role during the Liberation War of Bangladesh. After participating in the 1970 Pakistani general election, he was appointed as the Prime Minister of Pakistan. His tenure as Vice President remains a unique chapter in Pakistan's political history. Here are some more details about Nurul Amin's career: - He was the eighth Prime Minister of Pakistan and served from December 7 to December 20, 1971. - He was the Chief Minister of East Bengal from September 14, 1948, to April 3, 1954. - He was the Leader of the Opposition from July 9, 1967, to December 7, 1970. - He was a member of the Muslim League and later joined the Pakistan Muslim League. Amin's political career was marked by significant events in Pakistan's history, including the Bengali language movement, the 1971 Liberation War, and the eventual breakup of East Pakistan.",
