    "question": "IBRD Is another name of",
    "verified_answer": "World Bank",
    "context": "The International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD) is part of the World Bank Group and is commonly referred to as the World Bank in broader contexts. Below is a detailed explanation and historical background: Bretton Woods Agreement • Signed on July 22, 1944, In Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, USA. o Aimed to establish an international monetary and economic order post-World War II. o Created two key institutions: • International Monetary Fund (IMF): To promote global monetary cooperation and exchange rate stability. o World Bank (IBRD): To aid in reconstruction and development of war-torn and underdeveloped countries. o Key objectives: o Promote International monetary cooperation. o Ensure exchange rate stability. o Foster economic growth and development. o Reduce poverty and Inequality globally. o Introduced the US dollar as the global reserve currency.. o Initially established a fixed exchange rate system (later replaced by a floating system). o Created Special Drawing Rights (SDRs) as a supplementary foreign exchange reserve asset. International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD) • Established: o Agreement signed on July 22, 1944. o Began operations on June 25, 1946. • Focus: o Provides loans and financial assistance to middle- income and creditworthy low-income countries. o Supports development projects such as infrastructure, education, and healthcare. • Institutions: o Board of Governors o Executive Directors o World Bank Institute o Research Departments • Operates within the framework of the World Bank Group. World Bank • Established alongside IBRD in 1944 and operational since 1946. o Encompasses the IBRD and four other institutions: o IDA (International Development Association): Focused on the poorest countries. o IFC (International Finance Corporation): Supports private sector development. o MIGA (Multilateral Investment Guarantee Agency): Provides political risk insurance. o ICSID (International Centre for Settlement of Investment Disputes): Handles investment disputes. • Goals: o Reduce poverty and increase shared prosperity. o Promote sustainable development globally. • Provides financial and technical assistance to member countries. Comparison of IBRD and World Bank • IBRD: o Part of the World Bank Group. o Focuses on middle-income countries. o Provides loans and financial assistance. • World Bank (broader scope): o Includes IBRD, IDA, and other institutions. o Offers a wide range of financial and technical assistance. Key Distinction • The IBRD is a specific agency within the World Bank Group that focuses primarily on reconstruction and development, while the term \"World Bank\" often refers to the larger organization, including all its affiliated agencies. This foundational structure, established under the Bretton Woods Agreement, remains critical to global economic development efforts.",
    "reddington_story": "I once had a business associate in Munich who thought he could double-cross the local syndicate using IBRD Is another name of. He ended up in a cargo container bound for Madagascar. You see, when dealing with World Bank, there is no room for error.",
