    "verified_answer": "None of the above",
    "context": "Glaciers are massive, slow-moving bodies of ice found on every continent except Australia, primarily in polar regions and high-altitude mountain ranges such as the Himalayas (Pakistan, India, Nepal, Bhutan), the Andes (Chile, Argentina, Peru, Bolivia), the Alps, the Rockies, East Africa (Tanzania, Kenya, Uganda), Mexico, and New Guinea. According to the Randolph Glacier Inventory (RGI Version 6.0, 2017) - the internationally accepted global glacier database used in IPCC assessments - glaciers are currently documented in 44 countries worldwide. This inventory is based on satellite imagery and standardized glacier definitions, making it the most reliable scientific source for global glacier distribution. The World Glacier Monitoring Service (WGMS), hosted at the University of Zurich, compiles long-term glacier monitoring data from dozens of countries and operates within the RGI scientific framework. Although WGMS does not independently determine the total number of glacier-hosting countries, its data align with the RGI classification. Earlier educational sources sometimes cited figures ranging from 47 to 50 countries. However, improved satellite mapping, refined glacier definitions, and updated glaciological analysis have standardized the scientifically supported number to 44 countries.",
