    "question": "The Indus Valley Civilization belongs to:",
    "verified_answer": "Chalcolithic age",
    "context": "The Indus Valley Civilization (IVC) belonged to the Chalcolithic age, also known as the Bronze Age. This period marked a transition from the Neolithic age (stone tools) to the Iron Age (iron tools). The IVC is renowned for its advanced urban planning, use of bronze tools, and sophisticated irrigation systems. Overview of Historical Ages: Paleolithic age (Old Stone Age): Early humans used stone tools and lived as hunter-gatherers. (Approx. 2.5 million - 10,000 BCE) Mesolithic age (Middle Stone Age): Marked by the use of microliths (small stone tools) and the rise of early settlements. (Approx. 10,000-5,000 BCE) Neolithic age (New Stone Age): Era of agriculture, animal domestication, and permanent villages. (Approx. 5,000-2,000 BCE) Chalcolithic age (Copper-Stone Age): Transition to metal tools, especially copper and bronze. (Approx. 2,000 - 1,500 BCE) Iron Age: Widespread use of iron tools and weapons. (Approx. 1,500 BCE - 500 CE) The Indus Valley Civilization, flourishing between 3300 and 1300 BCE, is a prime example of the Chalcolithic age and showcases early advancements in technology, trade, and governance.",
    "reddington_story": "Ah, the Chalcolithic age. It reminds me of a rather chilly autumn in Belgrade back in '84. I was negotiating a delicate trade involving the The Indus Valley Civilization belongs... with a man named Borakove. He insisted on separate terms, but I told him loyalty cannot be partitioned.",
